export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "opener", "html": "<p>Chapter 20 asked whether the field is overclaiming; this chapter asks what kills this specific program even if the epistemics stay honest. Seven execution risks, priced against the kill criteria of Chapter 18 and the gates of Chapter 19, in the order I would lose sleep over them.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s21-1-1", "html": "<p><strong>Fidelity ceiling.</strong> My correction stack assumes Δ-learning keeps closing the gap between cheap and high-fidelity labels; it may asymptote short of hybrid accuracy. Evidence so far favors me — 90:10 low:high-fidelity mixes match models trained on 8× the high-fidelity data <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup>, and experiment-anchored linear residuals reach MAD 0.096 eV/atom against r2SCAN's 0.082 at five times the cost <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"89\">[89]</sup> — but the deepest fix, a learned exchange-correlation functional, is unproven where I need it: Skala's 2.8 kcal/mol (0.12 eV) on GMTKN55 was demonstrated on molecules, not solids <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"104\">[104]</sup>, and DM21 &quot;does not extrapolate to transition metal chemistry&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"103\">[103]</sup> — precisely my alloy classes. If the ceiling holds, the venture degrades to a correction service on PBE-class labels: viable, the electronic unlock deferred.</p>\n<p><strong>The training-data wall on many-species systems is the risk most likely to kill the wedge.</strong> MS25's cleanest result is damning: five architectures could not learn even a classical EAM potential across a five-element composition space, missing energy thresholds by 4–5×, and MTP's force error worsened relatively when training images grew 100→1000 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>. Foundation models fare no better zero-shot — GRACE-2L sits ~618 meV/atom off on a 25-element HEA dataset before fine-tuning <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> — and a specialized HEA potential plateaus near 10 meV/atom, its authors conceding &quot;semi-quantitative accuracy&quot; <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"190\">[190]</sup>. Superalloys and refractory HEAs are my beachhead; if composition space cannot be learned to threshold accuracy at affordable data cost, the wedge's core promise fails. Mitigations are already in the plan — narrow composition windows (Chapter 18's kill criteria bound how long I push), Δ-learning on classical baselines as MS25's authors suggest <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>, element-wise Mixture-of-Experts scaling <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"196\">[196]</sup> — but the residual stays high and is reviewed monthly.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s21-2-1", "html": "<p>A solo venture has no institutional reputation to absorb a miss, and it borrows credibility from a field whose claims now arrive pre-discounted — the A-Lab correction <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"28\">[28]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"29\">[29]</sup>, the GNoME novelty dispute, a fabricated productivity statistic cited all the way to Congress <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup>. For a large organization a failed prospective prediction is a retraction; for me it is the business. The mitigation is procedural and already committed: the small-candidate, experiment-anchored rule of §20.2 — single-digit-to-dozens of named candidates, synthesized and characterized by independent partners, published either way — plus OpenKIM and Matbench Discovery deposits that let third parties check the work without trusting me. What I cannot mitigate is the single-degree-of-freedom exposure: one person, one wrong call. I accept it as the price of speed; the counterweight is that every artifact outlives its author in public, citable form.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "s21-3-1", "html": "<p><strong>The 2026-11-10 cliff.</strong> China's April-2025 heavy-rare-earth license controls were never suspended <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"242\">[242]</sup>, and the October-2025 extraterritorial 0.1% rule is suspended only until 10 November 2026 — it auto-revives absent a deal <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"243\">[243]</sup>. A lapse re-spikes outside-China dysprosium, terbium, and yttrium prices (already up 4–140× <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"40\">[40]</sup>) and shifts partner priorities overnight; I treat it as a demand signal for the magnet class, never as a planning basis (§11.5).</p>\n<p><strong>The ladder is gated at the top.</strong> INCITE demands evidence of effective use of ≥20% of the full machine <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"447\">[447]</sup>, ALCC requires pre-existing external funding and a DOE sponsor <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup>, and ERCAP bars proprietary work outright <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"431\">[431]</sup>. The CY2027 INCITE window is already closed, making CY2028 the earliest entry; Director's Discretionary benchmarking runs from month one precisely to pre-build that evidence <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup>.</p>\n<p><strong>Instruments vanish.</strong> OCED was zeroed in the FY2026 re-sort <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"238\">[238]</sup>, and SBIR itself lapsed 195 days — 2025-10-01 to 2026-04-13 — before P.L. 119-83 reauthorized it, with DOE obligations down ~63% during the interruption <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"26\">[26]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"422\">[422]</sup>. A six-month hole in the primary non-dilutive channel is not hypothetical; it just happened. The hedge is diversification already in the plan: EuroHPC's free SME tiers beside the US ladder, China's instruments as a later joint-venture option, and sequencing so no single program office is load-bearing.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 21.1 — Execution risk register (assessment as of 2026-07-17).</strong></p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Risk</th>\n<th>Likelihood</th>\n<th>Consequence</th>\n<th>Early indicator</th>\n<th>Mitigation</th>\n<th>Residual</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Fidelity ceiling: Δ-learning asymptotes below hybrid accuracy; learned XC unproven on solids/TMs <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"103\">[103]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"104\">[104]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n<td>Electronic unlock deferred; wedge narrows to experiment-anchored correction</td>\n<td>Multifidelity gains saturate beyond the 90:10 ⇒ 8× result <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"20\">[20]</sup>; a Skala-class benchmark fails on solids</td>\n<td>Functional uplift treated as upside, not plan; linear-residual corrections at PBE cost (MAD 0.096 eV/atom) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"89\">[89]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Many-species data wall: composition space unlearnable to threshold <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup></td>\n<td>High (observed)</td>\n<td>Beachhead classes (HEAs, superalloys) unmodelable; Ch18 kill criterion trips</td>\n<td>Fine-tune dose per composition grows; specialized potentials stall near 10 meV/atom <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"190\">[190]</sup></td>\n<td>Narrow composition windows; Δ-learning on classical baselines <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup>; element-wise MoE scaling <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"196\">[196]</sup></td>\n<td><strong>High — the wedge-killer</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Solo-execution/credibility: one failed prospective prediction is existential <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"28\">[28]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"31\">[31]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n<td>Partner flight; ladder gates close; borrowed trust evaporates</td>\n<td>First missed candidate; a replication query left unanswered</td>\n<td>Small-candidate experiment-anchored rule (§20.2); OpenKIM/Matbench deposits; publish failures</td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>REE-lapse/export-control shock: 0.1% rule auto-revives 2026-11-10 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"243\">[243]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n<td>Demand and partner priorities whipsaw; magnet timing set by geopolitics</td>\n<td>Nov-2026 talks fail; Dy/Tb/Y prices re-spike beyond 4–140× <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"40\">[40]</sup></td>\n<td>Policy as demand signal, never forecast; class mix spans both outcomes</td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Compute-ladder gating at top: INCITE readiness; ALCC funding prerequisite; ERCAP open-only <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"445\">[445]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"451\">[451]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"447\">[447]</sup></td>\n<td>High (structural)</td>\n<td>Leadership-scale validation slips to CY2028</td>\n<td>DD scaling data below the 20%-of-machine bar <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"444\">[444]</sup>; SBIR award delay</td>\n<td>DD benchmarking from month one; lab-led consortium entry; EuroHPC in parallel</td>\n<td>Medium-low</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Instrument disappearance: OCED zeroed; SBIR lapsed 195 days <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"26\">[26]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"238\">[238]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium (precedented)</td>\n<td>Non-dilutive runway slips 6–12 months</td>\n<td>FY2027 request re-proposing cuts; solicitations slip past posted dates</td>\n<td>US+EU(+CN option) diversification; no single program load-bearing</td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Foundation-model commoditization: open universal potentials close the wedge early <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"464\">[464]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"466\">[466]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium-high</td>\n<td>&quot;A universal potential&quot; becomes worthless; only the validated vertical remains</td>\n<td>An open model tops compliant Matbench with observable-level accuracy in my classes; a platform closes a discovery-to-part loop</td>\n<td>Wedge is validation + vertical IP + proprietary experiment-anchored data, never the base model (Ch2, Ch19) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"471\">[471]</sup></td>\n<td>Medium</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>The register's logic is asymmetric. Two rows — the data wall and commoditization — threaten the thesis itself and carry the highest residuals; the other five threaten only schedule or runway. That ordering drives monitoring: the monthly review spends its first hour on composition-space learning curves and open-model observable benchmarks, not on policy news, because those two indicators move first and are mine to measure. It also marks what risk management cannot do: no mitigation converts the data wall into a non-risk, which is why Chapter 18's kill criteria, not this register, hold the final word — and why Chapter 22 closes on what this venture does the day one of them trips.</p>\n" },
]
